\begin_layout Subsection
Readers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The RFID reader is the most important element in an RFID system 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Active_Tags_1"

\end_inset

, because it is responsible to access the tag information and coordinate
 the complete reading process.
 The reader decodes the received data from the tags then sends this information
 to the middle-ware.
 The reader performance depends strongly on two factors: First, the Decoder
 architecture.
 Second, the antenna design.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Decoder architecture
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the previous discussion, this thesis focuses on passive RFID
 tags.
 Thus, the reader transmission power must be sufficient to feed the surrounding
 passive tags 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FSA4"

\end_inset

.
 These tags obtain energy from the transmitted signal using back-scattering
 technique.
 Back-scattering technique is the reflection of the reader’s carrier wave
 where it modulates the signal which includes the tag's data.
 Then, the reader detects the tag's response, processes the signal and reads
 the information sent by the tag.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Antennas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The polarization of the used antenna is one of the most critical issues
 which controls the identification performance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Antenna"

\end_inset

.
 In RFID systems, there are two types of antenna polarization: First, Linearly
 polarized antennas, in these antennas, the electrical field component of
 the transmitted signal is propagated in a plane (either vertical or horizontal).
 Linear polarized antennas must have a known RFID tag orientation and the
 RFID tag must be fixed upon the same plane as the antenna in order to get
 a consistent reading performance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Antenna_LP1"

\end_inset

.
 Second: Circularly polarized antennas, they emit electromagnetic fields
 in a corkscrew-like fashion.
 They broadcast electromagnetic waves on two planes making one complete
 revolution in a single wavelength.
 Compared to linear polarized antennas of the same gain, circular polarized
 antennas will have a shorter read range because they lose about 3 dB splitting
 their power across two separate planes.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Antenna_CP,AntennaCP"

\end_inset

.
 When deciding which type of antenna to choose for your RFID system, It
 depends on how the RFID tags should be oriented with respect to the antennas.
 If all the tags you need to read will be on the same plane and about the
 same height then you should consider a linear polarized antenna.
 If your tag orientation is not something that will be reliable or consistent,
 then you will likely need to use a circular polarized antenna.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Middle-ware
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In some applications, the tag identifier is used as an input for a database
 to get an information related to this object e.g.
 shipment orders, expiring date, etc.
 This kind of processing is done in a set of software tools called middle-ware.
 The EPCglobal standards 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "standard"

\end_inset

 define specifications for the middle-ware of RFID systems.
 Meanwhile, RFID systems are still an evolving technology.
 Thus, RFID middle-ware should be flexible enough so that it could be adapted
 to the future changes with minimal efforts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Frequency Bands
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar to how a radio must be tuned to different frequencies to hear different
 channels, RFID tags and readers have to be tuned to the same frequency
 in order to communicate.
 There are several different frequencies an RFID system can use.
 First, the Low Frequency (LF) 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "LF"
description "Low Frequency"

\end_inset

 band RFID systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "LF_RFID"

\end_inset

.
 LF tags have a long wave-length and are better able to penetrate thin metallic
 substances.
 Additionally, LF RFID systems are ideal for reading objects with high-water
 content, such as fruit or beverages, but the read range is limited to centimete
rs or inches.
 Typical LF RFID applications include access control and animal tagging.
 However, LF RFID systems have a limited reading range with 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5$
\end_inset

 m.
 Second, the RFID systems have operated in High Frequency (HF) 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "HF"
description "High Frequency"

\end_inset

 band RFID systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HF_RFID"

\end_inset

.
 High-frequency tags work well on objects made of metal and can work around
 goods with medium to high water content.
 Typical HF RFID systems work in ranges of inches, but they can have a maximum
 read range of about 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 m.
 Typical HF RFID applications include tracking library books, patient flow
 tracking, and transit tickets.
 Third, the Ultra High Frequency (UHF) 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "UHF"
description "Ultra High Frequency"

\end_inset

 band RFID systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "UHF_RFID"

\end_inset

.
 UHF frequencies typically offer much better read range (approximate 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

 m) and can transfer data faster (i.e.
 read many more tags per second) than low- and high-frequencies.
 However, because UHF radio waves have a shorter wavelength, their signal
 is more likely to be attenuated (or weakened) and they cannot pass through
 metal or water.
 Due to their high data transfer rate, UHF RFID tags are well suited for
 dense applications, such as boxes of goods as they pass through a gate.
 Microwave RFID tags are usually smaller than UHF tags and have the larger
 reading range.
 Microwave tags, due to low demand, are more expensive than UHF tags, but
 they share the same advantages and disadvantages.
 
\end_layout

