\begin_layout Subsection
Tag Collisions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This type of collision is the most common type of collision in dense RFID
 systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Tags_collision_2,Tags_collision_1,Tags_collision_3,Tags_collision_4"

\end_inset

.
 In such systems, we have a single RFID reader and multiple tags as shown
 in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Multiple-tags-to"

\end_inset

.
 The main objective is to identify all tags in the reading area in the minimum
 possible time.
 However, in dense networks, the number of tag collisions increase, which
 decrease the reading efficiency, and hence increase the reading time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tags anti-collision protocols can be classified into two main types: Physical
 layer protocols and MAC layers protocols.
 The main motivation of this thesis is to minimize the total identification
 time for a dense and passive RFID network.
 Therefore, in the following chapters, there are different proposals to
 enhance the MAC layer anti-collision protocols taking into consideration
 the physical layer parameters.
 
